<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   ASIS Bribes Report Under Investigation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK3001090094 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0800 
GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK3001090094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Malaysia and Australia will investigate whether 
opposition leaders in the country have received bribes from the 
Australian Secret Intelligence Service, ASIS, as reported by an 
Australian newspaper. Foreign Minister Datuk Abdullah Ahmad 
Badawi said if the report by THE SUNDAY TELEGRAPH is true, it is 
a serious matter and it shows foreign interference in Malaysia's 
affairs. He said the matter was among several issues he 
discussed with Australian High Commissioner to Malaysia John 
Dauth when the latter called on him at the ministry yesterday. 
He added that Malaysia and Australia will try to verify the 
report. So far it is only a press report. 
  Speaking to newsmen in Kuala Lumpur, Datuk Abdullah also 
stressed that his meeting with Dauth was fixed some time ago and 
had nothing to do with the report. According to the report, 
ASIS agents had paid thousands of Australian dollars to certain 
senior political leaders in Malaysia and Singapore since they 
became members of parliament. Government leaders and DAP 
[Democratic Action Party] leaders have strongly criticized the 
report and called on Canberra to name those involved if the 
allegations were indeed true. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

