<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sabah Ruling Party Branches Dissolved in Fracas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK3001145194 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in Malay 
1300 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK3001145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Malay </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The latest news on the political crisis affecting 
the [PBS] Sabah United Party is that as many as 42 PBS branches 
have been dissolved because they have opposed the party leaders' 
decision to nominate (Koh Tong) to run in Bengkoka in next 
month's state elections. The dissolved branches have more than 
1,000 PBS members who have accused him of failing to develop the 
constituency. The dissolution of the branches was confirmed by 
(Bonong Mulung), a PBS official in Bengkoka. Members of the 
dissolved branches were disappointed with PBS leaders who had 
refused to listen to their views. 
  Meanwhile, (Tayu Memayu), a PBS member of parliament who 
decided to quit the party said his main reason for quitting was 
that the PBS would not be able to lead the state and promote a 
multiracial society in Sabah. He said PBS leaders have always 
given priority to one ethnic group only, adding that this would 
worsen the state's racist policy. People now believe that if 
PBS is returned to power, the hope for an economic recovery in 
Sabah will be dashed. 

</TEXT>

