<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Air Services With Pakistan Gets Boost </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2801135894 Singapore BUSINESS TIMES in English 28 Jan 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> BK2801135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Singapore BUSINESS TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Singapore and Pakistan have agreed to further 
liberalize their air services agreement, the Civil Aviation 
Authority of Singapore (CAAS) said on 27 January. Effective 
immediately, the revised agreement allows each country's 
designated airline to operate four-weekly services using any 
aircraft type between the two countries. Now Singapore Airlines, 
SIA, operates one weekly Boeing B747 and two weekly Airbus A310 
services to Karachi, with a total weekly seat capacity of 767 
seats. 
  For its part, Pakistan International Airlines operates three 
weekly A310 services to Singapore, providing a total weekly 
capacity of 204 seats. 
  Both airlines plan to increase their services this year, 
CAAS 
said. 

</TEXT>

