<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Waives Visas, Bans Timber Exports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2901104794 Phnom Penh AKP in French 1029 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2901104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh AKP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh 28 Jan (AKP) -- The Cambodian Government 
has decided to waive entry visas for Cambodia for visits of two 
weeks or less. 
  This decision was made on Wednesday, 26 January, at a 
Council 
of Ministers meeting chaired by Prince Krompreah Norodom 
Ranariddh and His Excellency Hun Sen, first and second prime 
ministers of the Royal Government of Cambodia respectively. The 
decision will be effective as of 1 March 1994. At present, 
foreigners must pay $20 for an entry visa at Pochentong Airport. 
  Concerning agricultural development for the period of 
1994-95, the meeting decided to impose a ban on the export of 
logs and timber, but it still authorizes the exploitation of 
wood for local needs. 
  With regard to rubber exploitation, the government has 
decided in principle to privatize rubber production. It also 
examined the project for palm oil cultivation, saying it favored 
foreign and local investments in that sector. 
  The government has also adopted [number indistinct] May as 
Water Policy Day. On that day, all citizens should participate 
in work to construct irrigation systems. They should work on 
these projects for 15 days per year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

