<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Religious Leader Billy Graham Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Speech at 30 Jan Meeting Cited </H4>
<F P=102> SK3101014294 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2210 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK3101014294 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2210 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. religious leader Billy Graham, who is currently 
visiting our country, gave a speech at the People's Great Hall 
of Study on 30 January. 
  Saying that he had the great honor of meeting with the great 
President Kim Il-song, Reverend Graham said he rejoiced over the 
meeting. Noting that he is currently reading the great leader's 
memoirs zealously, he said: After having learned the fact that 
Christian followers actively supported the great President Kim 
Il-song's revolutionary activities through his memoirs, I was as 
delighted as the followers were. He added that Rev. Son Pyong-no 
had helped President Kim Il-song a great deal and noted that the 
reverend's family enjoyed being with President Kim Il-song. The 
great leader is a strong and wise leader. 
  He continued to say that he is well acquainted with the dear 
leader and stated that all DPRK people highly respect him. 
Recalling the fact that this is his second visit, he said: New 
streets are laid in Pyongyang. Pyongyang is beautiful, clean, 
and brilliant. A smile is on everybody's face and I can clearly 
read the DPRK people's state of mind. I can never forget my 
Pyongyang visit. 
  Touching on the fact that the DPRK people experienced agony 
and sorrow for almost half a century due to the country's 
division, Rev. Graham said: I can feel their agony and sorrow 
deeply. However, I cannot fully understand those feelings since 
I am not a party concerned. As I said two years ago during my 
Pyongyang visit, the United States and the former Soviet Union 
are responsible for the Korean division. The two countries 
pursued their interests in Korea, a weak power. Even nowadays, 
there are many cases of big powers demanding sacrifices from 
weak powers. I hope my current visit will contribute to reunify 
Korea and promote DPRK-U.S. relations. I visited your country 
out of responsibility that I will do my utmost for peace and 
reconciliation. I would like to pray for the great President 
Kim Il-song and thank the leaders [yongdoja] of the DPRK. 
  Kang Yong-sop, chairman of the Central Committee of the 
Korean Christian Federation; and Chong Chae-chol, chairman of 
the Central Committee of the Korea Catholics Association; 
religious followers and residents of Pyongyang were present. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

