<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Religious Leader Billy Graham Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Interviewed by Reporters 31 Jan </H4>
<F P=102> SK3101131894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1051 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3101131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 31 (KCNA) -- U.S. religious 
leader Rev. Billy Graham now on a visit to the Democratic 
People's Republic of Korea was interviewed by reporters in 
Pyongyang today. 
  "The most memorable was that I had an opportunity of 
spending 
private times and the lunch with the great leader," he said. 
  Referring to his visit to Kim Il-song University and the 
three revolution exhibition, he said: "I have been fully 
interested in large machinery and also the beautiful clothes 
that you are making in this country." 
  "The whole of the trip to the DPRK has been a wonderful 
experience and I'll never forget being among the people of this 
country," he said. 
  Recalling that he read the great leader's New Year address, 
He said: "Wherever I go, various countries have economic 
problems. We, in the United States, have same serious economic 
problems. 
  "The great leader is looking far ahead, and it seems what 
can 
be done now will help you in the future." 
  Turning to the moral and spiritual life of the Korean 
people, 
he said: "I see the responsible people and hear the beautiful 
singing. I say the order is disciplined here among the people." 
  "`The 10-point programme of the great unity of the whole 
nation for the reunification of the country' needs a great deal 
of study," he said, stressing "I am for the unification of the 
country." 
  "The great leader has said that he hopes the country's 
reunification would be done during the 1990s. So do I," the 
pastor noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

