<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Official Warns of Sanctions on Market Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901080294 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 Jan 94 
Evening Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2901080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, JIJI -- A senior U.S. Government 
official warned on 26 January that if the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks end in failure, the United States would use 
sanctions as a weapon to press Japan to open its market. 
President Clinton met on 25 January with other U.S. Government 
officials to review the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks. 
The same senior U.S. Government official made it clear that 
during the meeting, President Clinton approved of U.S. 
negotiators taking a tough stance and making no concessions at 
the bilateral economic framework talks. 
  The same senior U.S. Government official also disclosed that 
during the meeting, a U.S. official, while pointing out that no 
substantial progress has been made in the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks, stressed the need for both Japan and the United 
States to work to make a success of the Japan-U.S. summit talks 
scheduled for 11 February, and asserted that the talks should 
hammer out trade accords beneficial to the United States. 

</TEXT>

