<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Call for Numerical Targets Widely Rejected </TI></H3>
<H4>   MITI Official: `Inconceivable' </H4>
<F P=102> OW2901223694 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2901223694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A senior official in the U.S. Association of 
Automobile Industries has said that at Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks, U.S. negotiators had asked their Japanese 
counterparts to go along with a U.S. demand for setting a target 
for selling 100,000 American-built cars three years later on the 
Japanese market. Commenting on the U.S. official's remark at a 
regular news conference on 27 January, Hideaki Kumano, 
administrative vice minister of the Ministry of International 
Trade and Industry [MITI], said: "The Japanese Government cannot 
commit itself to goods that Japanese consumers buy. The U.S. 
demand cited by the official is out of the question and an 
inconceivable concept." 

</TEXT>

