<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Call for Numerical Targets Widely Rejected </TI></H3>
<H4>   Academic Group: `Unreasonable' </H4>
<F P=102> OW2901105094 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Jan 
94 Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2901105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The "Scholars Group Against Managed Trade," 
composed of 154 Japanese and foreign economists and political 
scientists (headed by Kazuo Ueda, a professor at the Economics 
Department of Tokyo University), held a news conference on 27 
January to announce its policy proposal against setting 
numerical targets which the United States has sought at the 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks. As for the numerical 
targets, the policy proposal criticized it as "something that 
promotes government-led managed trade." The policy proposal 
warned that if Japan accepts numerical targets, it would bring 
economic and political losses to Japan. 
  The policy proposal pointed out that "if the Japanese 
Government leads efforts to increase Japan's imports, Japan 
would face unreasonable trade demands from the United States. If 
Japan failed to meet the numerical targets, it would run into 
U.S. sanctions." The policy proposal also pointed out: "If Japan 
rejects the U.S. demand for setting numerical targets, it would 
be highly praised for protecting free trade, an asset of the 
entire world." 
  Meanwhile, the policy proposal stressed that the Japanese 
Government should expand opportunities for foreign access to the 
Japanese market, and address price differentials between Japan 
and other nations by relaxing bureaucratic regulations and 
rigorously enforcing the Antimonopoly Law. The policy proposal 
also urged the Japanese Government to work out plans for their 
promotion and announce the plans at home and abroad. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

