<H3> <TI>   U.S. Call for Numerical Targets Widely Rejected </TI></H3>
<H4>   Business Leaders: Continue Opposition </H4>
<F P=102> OW3101092294 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 31 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3101092294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa invited on 30 
January business leaders, including Nikkeiren [Japan Federation 
of Employers Associations] President Takeshi Nagano, Toyota 
Motor Corp. Chairman Shoichiro Toyoda, and Nomura Securities 
adviser Setsuya Tabuchi, to the Prime Minister's Official 
Residence. During this meeting which lasted about one hour, 
they exchanged views on ways to handle the Japan-U.S. summit 
talks scheduled on 11 February. Discussions focused mainly on 
the auto issues of the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks which 
are experiencing rough sailing. Business leaders brought up 
various requests and said: "Japan should maintain its opposition 
to the U.S. demand for setting numerical targets." 

