<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Official Outlines Auto Talks Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901045894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 29 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2901045894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 January </F>
Morning Edition] 
  [Text] Sozaburo Okamatsu, deputy vice minister of 
international trade and industry, in a news conference on 28 
January revealed the outline of a draft agreement presented by 
Japan at talks on the auto sector in the current round of 
Japan-U.S. economic consultations. The main points are 
proposals on the use import figures of finished automobiles by 
Japan as objective criteria, and an evaluation of import 
performance and discussion of remedial measures every six 
months. But Okamatsu admitted there remained a big gap in views 
between Japan and the United States, saying, "In the talks in 
Washington early this week I could not see any change in the 
U.S. demand for numerical targets, including future numbers." 
  The Japanese draft agreement proposes promoting cooperation 
among private companies, and using as objective criteria import 
figures for finished automobiles, the number of imported-auto 
dealers, and figures on U.S.-made auto parts bought by Japanese 
plants in the United States. 
  It proposes using as criteria only the numbers of actual 
purchases in the past, and not quantity or the future growth 
rate of automobile imports. 
  The draft also presents necessary future actions such as the 
sale of right-hand drive cars by U.S. companies and 
participation by U.S. parts makers in designing finished cars. 
It proposes conducting regular evaluation to determine progress 
in this area. Explaining the role of the government, Okamatsu 
said, "It will not go beyond providing support for business 
meetings and creating an atmosphere that encourages 
private-sector cooperation, such as through the provision of 
loans for the promotion of imports for instance." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

