<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy to U.S. Urges Presummit Draft Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2701121494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 26 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2701121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Shigeru Omago; from NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
26 January Evening Edition] 
  [Text] Washington, 25 Jan -- At a news conference on 25 
January, Takakazu Kuriyama, Japanese Ambassador to the United 
States, said: "Japan should urgently work out pump-priming 
measures, including a draft fiscal 1994 budget, to show its will 
to fulfill an economic responsibility." In this way, he 
stressed the need for Tokyo to compile the draft 1994 budget 
before the Japanese-U.S. summit talks take place on 11 February. 
Noting that Washington has put great expectations on Japan's 
pump-priming measures, a Japanese diplomatic source in the 
United States also said: "A delay in formulating 
economy-boosting measures is against Japan's interests. It also 
annoys people of the world." 
  During the news conference, Ambassador Kuriyama referred to 
the ongoing Japanese-U.S. framework trade talks in Washington. 
He said: "Both Japan and the United States should remember the 
starting point of the talks," expressing an apprehension over 
the situation in which Japanese and U.S. negotiators continue 
confronting each other over whether or not objective criteria 
should be set. He added: "Japan agreed last July to reduce its 
current account surplus and increase imports, and that was the 
starting point." His remark indicates that both Japan and the 
United States need to make concessions during the talks. 
  Regarding the prospect for the two sides making compromises, 
Kuriyama said: "Tokyo and Washington earlier agreed during 
construction talks to set criteria to gauge the openness of the 
Japanese construction market. This becomes a precedent and will 
be good for reference." In this way, he indicated that Japan 
would comply with the U.S. demand for setting criteria if they 
are yardsticks to evaluate results. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

