<DOCNO> FBIS3-48869 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas020__a94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-020-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa, Kumagai Meet on U.S. Framework Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101042494 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3101042494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 29 January, Hiroshi Kumagai, minister of the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry [MITI], discussed 
with Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa the issue of how to 
proceed with the deadlocked Japan-U.S. economic framework talks 
in the future, in consideration of the Japan-U.S. summit talks 
to be held on 11 February. 
  It is considered that regarding the macroeconomic policy as 
well as individual priority sectors, "a well-balanced accord 
will be indispensable" at the summit talks (as stated by a 
senior MITI official). Hosokawa and Kumagai seem to have 
confirmed the plan of working out a macroeconomic policy, about 
which the United States has expressed strong concern, which in 
turn may lead to overall success at the framework talks. 
  On the other hand, concerning individual sectors, Prime 
Minister Hosokawa and MITI Minister Kumagai have once again 
confirmed the stance of rejecting the U.S. demand for setting 
numerical targets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

