<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura Book Suggests `Rivalry' With Ozawa </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2501043194 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 25 
Jan 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2501043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 January </F>
Morning Edition] 
  [Text] Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura has 
published a book entitled: "Japan, a Small But Brilliant Nation" 
[Chisaku Tomo Kirari to Hikaru Kuni Nippon]. As if reacting to 
the notion of a "normal nation" [futsu no kuni] advocated in 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa's 
book: "A Plan to Rebuild Japan" [Nihon Kaizo Keikaku], Takemura 
proposes building Japan into a country which is small, but has a 
unique identity. Takemura and Ozawa, who are rumored to 
conflict in the ruling coalition parties, have apparently shown 
their sense of rivalry even in their books. Takemura's book 
directly refutes Ozawa's ideas. For instance, while Ozawa 
advocates the participation of the Self-Defense Forces in UN 
operations to make active international contributions, Takemura 
writes: "I do not agree with such ideas." 
  While Takemura's aides stress: "This is not meant to clarify 
his relations with Mr. Ozawa," the book says: "When we cooperate 
with other political parties, the basis will be ideas on the 
Constitution, the future and image of Japan, international 
contributions...we would like to work hand in hand with 
political parties which share our ideas and will work with us 
toward a common goal." As Japan faces the second stage of the 
process of political realignment, there is bound to be more 
controversy between the two men. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

