<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resumption of Humanitarian Aid to Burma Planned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2401195794 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2401195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 23 January, the government decided firmly to 
resume grant aid to Myanmar [Burma], which is currently ruled by 
a military dictatorship. As for changes in the State Law and 
Order Restoration Council's (SLORC) policy on human rights, the 
government has judged that "because gradual improvements have 
been observed in the country's situation concerning human 
rights, this opportunity should be taken to seek a policy of 
dialogue" (as stated by a Foreign Ministry source). 
  Specifically, it is expected that a small-scale aid program 
in which 3 million-5 million yen will be extended in each 
instance to purchase medical equipment and drugs for hospitals 
will be implemented by the end of the current fiscal year. This 
is to be done through such nongovernment organizations (NGO) as 
the Burmese Red Cross and Doctors Without Borders. Ever since a 
military coup took place in Burma in 1988, Japan has as a rule 
suspended all new aid programs to that country, except for 
emergency humanitarian aid. 
  Starting in April 1992, when General Than Shwe became 
chairman of the SLORC, the Burmese military dictatorship has 
released political prisoners, ceased attacks against ethnic 
minorities, and lifted martial law. It has also permitted 
meetings between opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi (a Nobel 
Prize winner), who has been under house arrest, and her family. 
Such changes have thus been noted in the government's clampdown 
policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48878 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas020__a94021" </HT>


