<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-020 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Malaysian Understanding Sought </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK3101081194 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0600 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK3101081194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Indonesian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["From the press review"] </F>
  [Text] The daily MERDEKA highlights the dispute over the 
islands of Sipadan and Ligitan. The daily understands 
Malaysia's apprehension if the International Court of Justice 
confirms Indonesian ownership of the two disputed islands 
because the sea lanes from Tawau to Malaysia's Exclusive 
Economic Zone situated in the Sulawesi Straits will be under 
Indonesian control. However, MERDEKA hopes that Malaysia will 
discard such a narrow-minded perception and will instead adopt a 
far-sighted attitude. 
  The daily reiterates that Indonesia has no intention 
whatsoever of putting Malaysia in a disadvantageous position. 
It recalls that Southeast Asia was once a kingdom alternatively 
ruled by sovereign rulers in the southern part of the Malay 
archipelago and in the Malay Peninsula. It adds: Why can't the 
fact that Singapore -- the majority of whose population is not 
of Malay stock -- is able to cooperate with Indonesia in 
developing the Riau islands serve as an example for Indonesia 
and Malaysia -- whose peoples have the same forefathers -to have 
good relations? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48895 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas020_j_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-020 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alatas Reiterates Support for Bosnia Arms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2901131094 Jakarta ANTARA in English 1204 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2901131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta ANTARA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jakarta, Jan 29 (ANTARA) -- In response to recent 
talks between President Suharto and Bosnian President Alija 
Izetbegovic, Indonesia plans to post an RI [Republic of 
Indonesia] ambassador in Sarajevo, Bosnia, this year. 
  Foreign Minister Ali Alatas told the press after 
inaugurating 
Syam Sumanagara as inspector general at the Foreign Ministry 
here over the weekend that the realization of the plan to open 
full diplomatic ties with Bosnia should be implemented soon. 
  "We are just waiting for a decision on who will be appointed 
Indonesian ambassador to Bosnia," he said, adding that Bosnia is 
also considering a reciprocal step. 
  The plan to open full diplomatic ties between Indonesia and 
Bosnia has been discussed by President Suharto and Bosnian 
President Alija Izetbegovic, who visited Indonesia recently. 
  Alatas said that Indonesia will maintain its stance to 
support Bosnia on the issue of the lifting of arms embargo 
imposed by the United Nations to Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  He said that Indonesia also backs Bosnia's rejection to the 
idea or resolution of lands division in the region. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48896 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas020_j_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-020 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Settlement Chances </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2901100994 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0000 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2901100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Indonesian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking to newsmen at the Sukarno-Hatta 
International Airport on his return from a three-day visit to 
Yemen yesterday, Foreign Minister Ali Alatas expressed his 
opinion that the Bosnia-Herzegovina problem could probably be 
settled through the Nonalignment Movement, NAM and the Islamic 
Organization Conference, ICO, because of the larger number of 
countries involved in the issue. Minister Ali Alatas was 
optimistic that if a conference was hosted by the Nonalignment 
Movement and ICO, there was a hope that peace would be restored 
to Bosnia when compared to the unilateral conferences held in 
Geneva. 
  According to the minister, a long series of conferences had 
already been held and Bosnia is concerned over the 
responsibility and attitude of the United Nations Security 
Council. 

</TEXT>

