<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev Agrees To Receive Clinton Envoy 13 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2912195393 Sofia BTA in English 1849 GMT 29 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> AU2912195393 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, December 29 (BTA) -- President of the 
Republic Dr. Zhelyu Zhelev agreed to receive on January 13, 1994 
Mrs. Madeleine Albright in her capacity as special envoy to 
Bulgaria of U.S. President Bill Clinton, reporters learnt today 
from Dr. Zhelev's foreign policy advisor Kamen Velichkov. 
  Mr. Velichkov specified that the purpose of the visit of 
Mrs. 
Albright, who is U.S. permanent representative to the United 
Nations, will be to brief the Bulgarian head of state on the 
results of the NATO summit due in Brussels on January 10. 
  Mr. Velichkov pointed out that some time ago President 
Clinton sent a message to Dr. Zhelev, expressing his agreement 
and desire to take into account Bulgaria's position on the 
exceedingly important and relevant issue of Bulgaria's bid to 
join the North Atlantic Alliance. 
  In his reply, Dr. Zhelev's advisor said, the Bulgarian 
president agrees to receive Mrs. Albright and reaffirms his and 
this country's principled and reasoned position in favour of 
Bulgaria's cooperation with NATO and its future participation in 
the alliance. 
  One important point in Dr. Zhelev's reply message is the 
fact 
that Bulgaria became the first country in Eastern Europe whose 
legislature took a stand on this pressing issue, which is 
important for all Central and East European countries, Mr. 
Velichkov said. Last week the Bulgarian Parliament voted a 
declaration on cooperation with NATO. 
  The message is part of an ongoing dialogue which started at 
the meeting of the two presidents earlier this year and which 
will continue with the forthcoming visit to Bulgaria by the 
special envoy of the U.S. President, Mr. Velichkov said. 

</TEXT>

