<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TANJUG Reports Mobilization of Bosnian Croats </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012213493 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2058 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3012213493 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Zagreb, December 30 (TANJUG) -- The Croatian 
Helsinki Committee warned Thursday [30 December] that mass 
mobilization was carried out in the past few weeks in the 
Republic of Croatia of those born in Bosnia-Herzegovina in order 
to send them to the battle fronts in this war-torn former 
Yugoslav republic. 
  A committee statement said several thousand people have 
already been mobilized. They were at the barracks of the 
Croatian Army and wearing uniforms without any insignia. Noting 
that those mobilized were citizens of Croatia, the committee 
noted that the Croatian authorities "did not adhere to 
international provisions" which "most strongly forbid sending 
soldiers of one state to fight in another state." 
  A civil war raged in Bosnia-Herzegovina for more than 20 
months between the local Serbs, Moslems and Croats. The Bosnian 
Croats have from the very beginning been assisted by several 
tens of thousand of troops of the regular Army of the Republic 
of Croatia. The Croatian Helsinki Committee demanded the 
Croatian authorities immediately halt such activities, condemn 
them and promise a thorough and urgent enquiry as well as open 
disciplinary and court proceedings against the officials 
involved. 
  The statement also demanded an enquiry into the fate of all 
the soldiers, Croatia's citizens, sent to Bosnia-Herzegovina 
whose whereabouts were presently unknown, as well as the return 
of all those mobilized and already sent to Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
The committee, as set out, was in possession of documents 
showing that disciplinary measures were taken against the 
soldiers serving in Croatia's Army who have refused to go to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina as well as that they were threatened with 
court-martial. 
  Some of the soldiers who refused to take part in the latest 
preparations for going to Bosnia-Herzegovina "were beaten up at 
the barracks," while others were threatened "to have their 
citizenship certificates taken away and inviting trouble for 
their families," the statement of the Croatian Helsinki 
Committee said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

