<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Refugee Convoy Arrives in Split </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3112081493 Paris AFP in English 2341 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> AU3112081493 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Dec 31 (AFP) -- A convoy carrying about 750 
Bosnian Moslems and Croats civilians out of Sarajevo arrived 
late Thursday [30 December] at the Croatian port of Split, the 
official Croatian agency HINA said. The refugees, mainly women, 
children and elderly, left Sarajevo on Tuesday evening on board 
16 buses. They will be housed temporarily in a sports centre in 
Split, before being transferred to refugee camps or leaving for 
new lives in another country. 
  Many of the refugees had no documents with them, which 
created long hold-ups at the Croatian-Bosnian border, the Croat 
refugee office said quoted by HINA. Bad roads and a spate of 
technical hitches also delayed the convoy's progress. UNHCR 
spokesman Ray Wilkinson said earlier Thursday in Sarajevo: "It 
was not anticipated that it would take so long." 
  Wilkinson said the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) 
was going to feed the evacuees before the last leg of the 
journey Thursday from Metkovic on the Croatian border to Split, 
120 kilometres (70 miles) to the north. "These people are 
probably quite hungry, since they had only a few food supplies 
with them when they left Sarajevo on Tuesday," he said. 
  A group of 150 Bosnian Serbs evacuated the same day, heading 
for Belgrade, arrived in Serbia on Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

