<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Reveals Popularity of Politicians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3012172693 Prague CTK in English 1604 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> AU3012172693 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Dec 30 (CTK) -- Miroslav Sladek, chairman 
of the extreme right Assembly For the Republic-Czechoslovak 
Republican Party (SPR-RSC), is the least trusted Czech 
politician, a poll conducted by the Institute for Public Opinion 
Research (IVVM) in early December revealed. Sladek, mistrusted 
by 76 percent of the polled, was followed by Chairman of the 
Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL) 
Josef Lux and Interior Minister Jan Ruml (Civic Democratic 
Party, ODS) with 57 percent of mistrust for each. 
  The least known politician (62 percent of Czechs do not know 
him) is Jan Krycer, chairman of the HSDMS (Self-Governing 
Democracy Movement For Moravia and Silesia, 14 deputies in a 
200-seat parliament). He is followed by communist politicians 
Miroslav Grebenicek and Jaroslav Ortman with 58 and 57 per cent, 
respectively. Five and seven percent of the polled do not know 
President Vaclav Havel and Premier Vaclav Klaus, while Sladek is 
not known by 9 percent. 

</TEXT>

