<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Seeks Help From IMF </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012130893 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1041 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3012130893 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, December 30 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Prime 
Minister Radoje Kontic has asked the general director of the 
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to dispatch a mission to 
Yugoslavia to acquaint itself with the government's 
anti-inflationary programme and a monetary system reconstruction 
programme prepared for January 17. Letters with the same 
content were sent on Wednesday to the president of the World 
Bank amd the president of the European Bank for Reconstruction 
and Development. Kontic wrote that inflation of more than 20 
per cent a day was causing the withdrawal of goods, services and 
factors of production from the market. 
  The government is aware of the urgency of stabilizing the 
national currency and putting the financial system back on its 
feet in order to save the economy, he wrote. The inflation is 
especially hard on the sick and the poor, Kontic wrote. The 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia is hit by the world's highest 
inflation as a result of international economic sanctions 
imposed 19 months ago. Production is paralyzed, imports and 
exports are banned, and the country's assets are frozen in 
foreign banks. Retail prices rose by more than 20,000 per cent 
in November alone. 
  Kontic invited an IMF mission to visit Yugoslavia any time 
before January 14. The start of monetary reconstruction is 
scheduled for January 17. The government has requested the UN 
Sanctions Committee to take action to release Yugoslavia's 
assets abroad (National Bank reserves and commercial bank 
deposits), Kontic wrote. These funds would be used to prop up 
the national currency and soften the transition from 
inflationary financing to an economy backed by a sound currency, 
he wrote. The initiative for these activities was given by 
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, Kontic wrote. 
  A team of experts has advised Kontic to start monetary 
reconstruction on January 17 even if his request is turned down 
by the international institutions concerned. The experts 
estimate there will be a deficit of some 800 million [figure as 
received] during the first half of the year. The deficit, they 
say, could be covered by releasing the foreign currency reserves 
of the National Bank and commercial banks. This could be done 
by lifting the sanctions or finding other ways of giving 
Yugoslavia access to these funds. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

