<H3> <TI>   Train Drivers Agree To End Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0101215794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2115 GMT 1 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0101215794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 1 January (TANJUG) -- The independent 
train drivers' trade union of Serbia has adopted a decision to 
end the strike and immediately establish regular service 
throughout the territory of Serbia, the information center of 
the Belgrade public railway transport enterprise announced this 
evening. 
  There are no details in this laconic statement, which 
contains only one sentence, about the ending of the strike that 
has been going on since the day before yesterday in the 
afternoon, nor about what was agreed between employers' 
representatives and the government on the one hand, and the 
strike committee on the other. One thing, however, is certain: 
This was a particularly "nasty" strike in terms of its 
consequences for thousands of passengers who were unable to 
travel over the holidays and who suffered greatly in waiting 
rooms and on platforms. 

</TEXT>

