<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Miners End Strike; Power Back to Normal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112180093 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1713 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3112180093 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Dec 31 (TANJUG) -- Miners at Serbia's 
biggest coal mine Kolubara on Friday ended a three-day strike 
after negotiating a settlement with the authorities in the night 
between Thursday [30 December] and Friday. 
  Early on Friday afternoon, the Belgrade city transport was 
back to normal after its workers ended their several-hour 
stoppage. Like the workers in Kolubara, they went on strike 
demanding higher wages and better living standards. The strike 
of the 17,000 Kolubara workers in Lazarevac near Belgrade ended 
after the miners on Friday morning verified the agreement 
reached with the republic's electricity board and the government 
on Thursday night. The strikers demanded to receive their wages 
in German marks because of the galopping inflation which hit one 
million percent in December alone. 
  The disturbances in coal deliveries resulted in the 
suspension of operation of the thermal power plant Nikola Tesla 
in Obrenovac, which produces 50 percent of Serbia's overall 
electricity, due to which the Serbian electricity board started 
with several-hour brownouts on Thursday. Although the miners' 
strike has ended, it is not certain whether power supply in 
Serbia will be back to normal on Friday because of the 
disturbances in coal deliveries and electricity production or 
whether some parts of the republic will celebrate New Year's Eve 
in candlelight. 
  Dissatisfied with low wages, workers in the Belgrade city 
transport struck on Friday morning. The Serbian railways has 
been on strike for several days, along with some hospitals and 
gravediggers in Belgrade. A drastic fall in the living 
standards and record-high hyperinflation have been provoked by 
draconic U.N. sanctions introduced against Yugoslavia in late 
May of 1992. 
  Three-fourths of Serbia's industrial facilities have been 
standing still for months, while the remaining one-fourth 
operate at reduced capacities although they are not on strike. 
The average salary in Serbia is below 15 German marks, while 
one kilo of meat sells for 40 marks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48938 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu001_y_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-001 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Supports Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112151093 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1358 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3112151093 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 31 Dec (TANJUG) -- The presidency of the 
Serbian Renewal Movement [SPO] and Depos [Serbian Democratic 
Alliance] demand that the Serbian Government immediately fulfill 
the Kolubara miners demands, a SPO Presidency statement, 
forwarded to TANJUG today, says. 
  In its message of support to the miners, the SPO says that 
"the disgraceful truth is that in todays's Serbia loiterers and 
criminals get rewarded while miners cannot afford a crust of 
bread." 
  "The SPO and Depos resolutely support the view that the 
authorities who cannot secure at least two things: That no one 
in Serbia is hungry and that every citizen's salary is enough to 
feed himself and his family, must be removed," the statement 
says. 
  The Civic Forum's [nonnationalist intellectual group] 
statement, also forwarded to TANJUG, says that "the latest 
events show that the authorities are trying to provoke the 
introduction of a state of emergency." 
  "The strikes by public services of vital importance for the 
functioning of our state and for citizens' lives, such as 
electricity supplies, railroads and local transportation, show 
that the authorities have decided to use these events to justify 
the introduction of a state of emergency," the Civic Forum's 
statement says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48939 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu001_y_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-001 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgrade Facing Electricity Shortage </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112144693 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1216 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3112144693 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Belgrade, 31 Dec (TANJUG) -- Due to the shortage 
of electric power, Belgrade is now divided into only two blocs, 
instead of the previous four -- those having electricity and 
those not. It is not known for how long this situation will 
last; it depends on the resumption of normal coal production in 
the Kolubara complex, Miodrag Simic, the technical operations 
manager of the Belgrade Electricity board said at a news 
conference today. [passage omitted] 
  According to information available to the Belgrade 
Electricity Board it is not certain that the miners will go back 
to work and resume coal deliveries. According to Simic, if the 
power plant in Obrenovac does not resume work, half the Belgrade 
population will have only candles for light during New Year's 
Eve. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

