<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Drnovsek Warns Croatia on Mutual Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0201191794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1909 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0201191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, Jan 2 (TANJUG) -- Slovene Prime Minister 
Janez Drnovsek on Sunday warned the leadership of the 
neighbouring Republic of Croatia that `Slovenia may take a 
firmer stand towards Croatia as regards the resolution of mutual 
problems.' Drnovsek told Ljubljana Television that so far it 
has been Slovenia alone that has initiated talks, `sticking by 
what is termed a soft stand.' That was why Slovenia decided to 
`cool off relations for Croatia to realize that this problem 
must be of joint concern,' said Drnovsek. 
  In recent months, Slovene-Croatian relations have been 
broken 
off entirely, as was asserted also by Slovene Foreign Minister 
Lojze Peterle. One-time firm alliance between Ljubljana and 
Zagreb in breaking Yugoslavia has been affected by a series of 
outstanding territorial and other matters [sentence as received]. 
  The central problem is posed by a future sea border in the 
Piran Bay. Both sides adhere to their origiinal stands -- 
Slovenia insists on the current border, Croatia on a redrawn 
border. The settlement of the sea border issue, analysts 
believe, might engage also an international arbitration. In 
that case an additional weight would be put on what are at this 
time only minor territorial questions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

