<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa on Threat of `East-West Confrontation' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0201170094 Warsaw PAP in English 1647 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0201170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 2 -- President Lech Walesa said on 
Sunday [2 January] in an interview for the Italian daily LA 
STAMPA that there was a threat of new east-west confrontation 
like the cold war unless the European Union embraced the East 
European countries that had been in the Eastern European bloc. 
If the European Union and NATO do not admit the Eastern 
European countries, Russia would seek to re-assert its influence 
in the region, said the president. If Europe and NATO decided 
within a short period of time, six months at the most, to expand 
gradually towards the European countries that were communist, 
then the field of confrontation would diminish, Walesa stressed. 
He added that otherwise Russia will take the initiative, 
exercising economic pressures on Poland and countries more 
important than Poland like Ukraine. We will have to give in to 
compromises and the former Soviet bloc will organise itself 
again, concluded Walesa. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

