<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Responds to Claes on Christmas Truce </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112181693 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1647 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3112181693 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 31 Dec (TANJUG) -- Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the republic of Srpska, sent a letter today to 
Willy Claes, chairman of the European Union's council, in reply 
to his claim that the responsibility for the continuation of the 
conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina lay with the Serb side. 
  The letter says that this truce was being violated by Muslim 
extremists who, in Karadzic's words, are intolerant of Christian 
holidays. 
  "Dear Mr. Claes, I am deeply moved by your concern about the 
violations of the Christmas truce," President Radovan Karadzic 
says in his letter. He further stresses that, in this civil 
war, as in the previous two World Wars, the Serbs are exposed to 
vicious attacks by their neighbors of different denominations, 
especially during Orthodox Christian holidays. 
  Underlining that the Serbs would be thrilled if the Muslims 
ceased their military activities, the republic of Srpska 
president expressed his hope that Willy Claes, as chairman of 
the European Union's council, could influence the Muslim side to 
accept the peace plan drawn up thanks to Serb concessions. 

</TEXT>

