<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croats Accuse Muslims of `Greatest Crime' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012172293 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3012172293 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Defense Ministry of the Croat Republic of 
Herceg-Bosna pointed out in a special statement today that 
Muslim fundamentalists from the ranks of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army have committed the greatest crime yet in their brutal 
aggression against the Croat population of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
and its ancestral homes. The fate of the mass execution grounds 
in Uzdol, Maljin, Doljani, Trusina, Grabovica, and Mostar has 
befallen the village of Krizancevo near Vitez. 
  According to well-informed sources close to UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces], 50 of the 53 Croats abducted by Muslim 
fundamentalists in Krizancevo last week were brutally murdered 
while three are prisoners in a Zenica jail. A mass grave 
containing the remains of 35 massacred Croats has been found in 
Preocica while another one located in no-man's-land between the 
Muslim forces and Croatian Defense Council units contains the 
bodies of another 15, the statement says. 
  The Muslim Army is still refusing to allow international 
organizations and UNPROFOR access to the area between Krizancevo 
and positions held by the 3d Corps of the Muslim Army, where the 
Muslims had carried out the massacre. The liaison officer of 
UNPROFOR's British battalion today informed the command of the 
Vitez operational zone that the spokesman for the Muslim Army's 
3d Corps had declared that some 15 bodies of Krizancevo 
villagers could be found near the separation line and that 
another 35 were buried in a mass grave near the Muslim village 
of Preocica between Vitez and Zenica. The liaison officer 
failed to disclose any details about the crime but added that 
the head of the European observers and representatives of the 
International Red Cross were still trying to obtain the 3d 
Corps' permission to carry out an on-the-spot investigation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48969 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu001_i_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-001 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Correspondents Find `No Trace' of Massacre </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0101161594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 1 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0101161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The defeats suffered by the ustashas on the 
battlefields of Bosnia are most often described by the Croatian 
media as strategic retreats or, when a large number of 
casualties is at issue, as a massacre of civilians. It is 
obvious that Boban and Tudjman would like, in a rather 
masochistic way, to see Croats experiencing something similar to 
Ahmici and Stupni Dol [sites of massacres of Muslim civilians by 
Croat forces]. For several days this country's media have been 
citing a figure of 74 civilians killed in Krizancevo Selo. 
  The West European and other world TV broadcasters who are 
stationed only a few km from this village have not reported a 
single line about this case because they have, of course, found 
nothing to report. 
  Following the lies of the Croatian media, yesterday four 
European agencies, THE DAILY TELEGRAPH, CNN, the BBC, and 
REUTERS visited the site; they saw no trace of any massacre. 
The only thing they witnessed was the fact that the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina fighters in this area had scored yet another 
great military victory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48970 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu001_i_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-001 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic, Turkey's Demirel Discuss Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3012190993 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> AU3012190993 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Alija Izetbegovic, president of the Presidency of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, today held a telephone conversation with 
Suleyman Demirel, president of the Republic of Turkey. This was 
stated by the Information Service of the Presidency of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Expressing interest in events in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Demirel 
told President Izetbegovic that Turkey will use its influence in 
the international community so that the integrity of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina is preserved. President Demirel will 
exchange messages on this with U.S. President Clinton, British 
Prime Minister Major, German Chancellor Kohl, Egyptian President 
Mubarak, and others. 
  Turkish Prime Minister Tansu Ciller, who will be taking part 
in the NATO session scheduled for 8 January next year, will 
support the participation of NATO forces in the implementation 
of the peace agreement on Bosnia-Herzegovina, if such an 
agreement is reached. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

