<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Commander Criticizes Efforts for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112154193 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1500 
GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3112154193 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Bosnia General Briquemont, Gen. Morillon's 
successor, is increasingly bitter and is quite open about it. 
The Belgian general said that the activities of the UN force in 
Bosnia were completely paralyzed by the lack of personnel and 
political will. This inefficiency undermined the credibility of 
future UN operations. Interviewed in his office in the UN 
peacekeepers' barracks near Sarajevo hospital, Gen. Briquemont 
wondered whether the leaders of the three warring parties cared 
at all about the fates of their compatriots. They talk only 
about their war aims and objectives, he said, adding: I think 
that they like power above all else. 
  The United Nations, however, is also guilty in the general's 
eyes. It has voted resolution after resolution without giving 
itself the means to implement them effectively. There is a 
yawning gulf, he said, between all the UN resolutions and the 
means made available to implement them on the ground. The 
general estimated that he needed at least a further 10,000 men 
in order to carry out his mission in Bosnia. Instead of that, 
he said, France and Great Britain speak of withdrawing their 
contingents in the spring if there is no sign of solution to the 
conflict. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

