<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting Continues Over New Year </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0201155994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1542 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0201155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, January 2 (TANJUG) -- Heavy fighting 
continued in the former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
over the new year holidays, despite an agreement reached by the 
three warring sides to halt hostilities from December 23 until 
January 15. Moslem forces continued attacks on Serb positions 
and villages on fronts in the wider region of Doboj in northern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, the Doboj operative group of the Bosnian 
Serb army said on Sunday [2 January]. Moslem forces were the 
most active in the eastern part of the Ozren front, the source 
said. The villages of Milino Selo and Vozuca took the brunt of 
the attack. Moslem forces attacked Serb defence positions in 
the region of Foca and Cajnice in southeastern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina from the direction of Gorazde on Saturday 
night, the Herzegovina Corps in Bileca said on Sunday morning. 
  Moslem-Croat conflicts also continued last night and this 
morning in southern Bosnia-Herzegovina and in its central part. 
Croatian radio reported on Sunday morning that Moslem forces 
last night attacked Bosnian Croat positions in the region of 
Mostar with infantry and artillery weaponry. Moslem Radio 
Sarajevo said that Croatian forces fired more than a hundred 
shells on Blagaj in southern Bosnia-Herzegovina on new year's 
eve and on Saturday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

