<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman: Muslims Threatening Survival of Croats </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012230793 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2234 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3012230793 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, December 30 (TANJUG) -- Croatian President 
Franjo Tudjman stated Thursday [30 December] that the offensive 
of the Bosnian Moslems threatened the survival of the Croatian 
enclaves in central Bosnia and added he expected international 
pressure to prevent this, REUTERS has reported. In a television 
interview, Tudjman, whom the British news agency termed "patron 
of ethnic Croat forces in Bosnia's war," accused the army of the 
Bosnian Moslem Government of trying to push through to the 
Adriatic Sea and split Croatian territory. 
  "They even have plans to push through to the sea and split 
Croatia. Such plans are similar to the Serbs' plans. We can 
expect the world will put more pressure of the Moslem leadership 
(to stop fighting," Tudjman said in the interview. A civil war 
raged for 20 months in Bosnia between the local Moslems, Serbs 
and Croats. Regular troops of the Republic of Croatia were 
fighting on the side of the Bosnian Croats. 

</TEXT>

