<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akashi Says Japan `Must Contribute' Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0301160694 Paris AFP in English 1551 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0301160694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Jan 3 (AFP) -- Yasushi Akashi, the United 
Nations' new special representative in ex-Yugoslavia, said upon 
his arrival here Monday that Japan must contribute peacekeeping 
troops toward the conflict in the region. "Japan, which is now 
a major power, has to cooperate with European countries, with 
the United States, Canada and the other governments which are 
already deeply involved in restoring peace here in 
ex-Yugoslavia," Akashi said during a press conference. 
  "If Europeans are in Asia, why shouldn't Asians be in 
Europe," he said refering to UN peacekeeping troops deployed in 
Cambodia. 
  Akashi, 62, in his new assignment becomes the special UN 
representative in the former Yugoslavia and head of the UN 
Protection Force deployed in the region. He replaces Thorvald 
Stoltenberg who will retain his position as co-chairman of the 
Geneva peace talks on the Bosnian conflict. Akashi previously 
headed the UN force deployed in Cambodia. 
  Akashi later announced that a team of Japanese Government 
experts would soon arrive in former Yugoslavia to study how 
Tokyo could "extend its cooperation in order to help restore 
peace" to the region. He also said he was planning to 
reorganize some sections of UNPROFOR [United Nations Protection 
Forces], introducing elements which he had personally selected. 
He said he saw his role as helping to reestablish confidence 
between the three warring factions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49003 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu002_b_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-002 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

