<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Company Invites Bids To Modernize Kozloduy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0301154894 Paris AFP in English 1505 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0301154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, Jan 3 (AFP) -- The Bulgarian electricity 
company launched an invitation for tenders to modernise four 440 
megawatt nuclear units at the Kozloduy power station on Monday. 
The programme is to be financed by the nuclear safety fund of 
the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) and 
the tenders are to be opened on March 4 in the presence of 
bidders. 
  The first stage of improvements to make safe the four 
obsolete units of Soviet design was completed last week when the 
the oldest unit, which had been in service since 1974, was put 
back into operation. This unit had been closed in September 
1991 on the recommendation of the International Atomic Energy 
Agency. 
  Apart from the four units of 440 megawatts, the plant 
comprises two more modern units, each of 1,000 megawatts. The 
power station provides between 30 percent and 40 percent of 
energy used in Bulgaria. 

</TEXT>

