<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paks Nuclear Station Faces Storage Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0301181594 Budapest NEPSZABADSAG in Hungarian 29 Dec 93 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0301181594 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest NEPSZABADSAG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Correspondent's report: "The Fate of the Paks Nuclear </F>
Power Station Is Uncertain"] 
  [Text] If we do not find a safe solution to store the 
expended fuel within 18 months then the further operation of the 
Paks Nuclear Power Station Inc. may become doubtful. Should 
this happen, half of Hungary's energy production would be lost, 
Laszlo Kemenes, leader of the company's information service, 
said. 
  In the past, the expended fuel was transported to the Soviet 
Union. In the summer of 1992, the Russian parliament accepted 
an environmental protection law that bans the import of 
dangerous waste. In spite of this, in February 1993, Russia 
accepted expended fuel filling a railway carriage. However, it 
is not at all certain that it will again do this, although it 
has not indicated, either, that it will refuse to process waste 
from Paks in the future. The Ukrainian side has already 
indicated that it would let the deliveries pass through. 
Considering the favorable atmosphere of talks with the 
Russians, it cannot be excluded that future deliveries will be 
possible. As Hungary cannot expose itself to the decisions of 
other countries, a solution will definitely have to be found 
within a short time. 
  For five years, the used-up fuel elements has been stored in 
a resting basin at the Paks Nuclear Power Station, then they 
were transported in special containers. At the moment, the free 
storage capacity at Paks is enough for 18 months, therefore, if 
no solution is found in the coming 18 months then, failing all 
else, the nuclear power station might be halted. 
  Being aware of this situation, to safely solve the further 
placement of waste, the company had internationally announced 
bids for building a transitional storage, and this was won by 
the French-British GEC-ALSTHOM. This company, which has built 
several of this type of storage, will have to complete the 
reception building and the storage area in 18 months. Although 
temporarily, the Paks Nuclear power station would gain time 
through this 3 to 3.5 billion forints investment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49014 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu002_h_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-002 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Bank Devalues Forint by 1 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0101165194 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1600 GMT 1 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0101165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The forint will be devalued by 1 percent as of 3 
January. The decision was made by the Hungarian National Bank 
[MNB] within its scope of authority. The MNB gave the 
strengthening of the U.S. dollar on international foreign 
exchange markets as the reason for the decision. A communique 
points out that the measure is in line with the MNB's official 
exchange rate policy. 

</TEXT>

