<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ganic Says Owen Plan `Will Resolve Nothing' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0301230594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2100 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0301230594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ejup Ganic, member of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Presidency, today gave an interview to VJESNIK of Zagreb, the 
Slovene daily VECER, and FERAL of Split. 
  I am not an optimist when it comes to signing the agreement 
as envisaged by Lord Owen. Both the agreement and its draft 
will resolve nothing in Bosnia. In other words, it is merely an 
academic paper that neither tackles the essence nor raises the 
main issues facing this state. 
  We would like to avoid the war option but we expect Serbia 
to 
launch a new attack. The regime in Serbia sees the continuation 
of the war as crucial for its survival. However, they are not 
as strong as they think they are. They have artillery, criminal 
units, but they have no popular army. On the opposite side they 
are facing an army of volunteers. 
  As for the Croatian state, which has disintegrated on all 
fronts and which is trying to step up its aggression against a 
sovereign state, it is obvious that Tudjman's behavior is 
preparing the ground for sanctions against Croatia, Ganic 
stressed. 
  In eastern Bosnia, we will not allow homes and the land 
belonging to Bosniak Muslims to be taken over by a single Serb 
family. My message to the Serbs is this: Do not go there, do 
not move into houses and land that belong to someone else. 
Something terrible will happen to you, today, tomorrow, the day 
after tomorrow, or in six months, it does not matter. Those 
whom you have expelled have nowhere to go. They are strangers 
in both Sarajevo and Vienna. The solution is to return these 
people to where they came from, Ganic said. 
  The proposal for a union [in Bosnia-Herzegovina] will be 
difficult to implement, Ganic said. If we are to accept the 
proposal, at least 1 million people will have to be resettled. 
To resettle them we would need at least $2 million daily or 
about $700 million annually to relieve the misery of these 
people. The union proposal is not a serious one because it does 
not reflect reality. We are not in the process of setting up a 
Muslim state. We want to create a state of Bosnia with Croats, 
Serbs, and Bosniak Muslims living in it. I think that the idea 
of a Muslim state was planted on us and has, in the meantime, 
become transparent. Here the feeling of patriotism is much 
stronger than any other passion. I am in favor of Bosnia as a 
state of Bosniak Muslims, Serbs, and Croats but am not in favor 
of an artificial peace. I advocate the rule of law. 
  It is realistic to expect a turnabout in Croatia's policy in 
Bosnia. Its policy will hit rock bottom unless Tudjman has 
reached an agreement to hand over the occupied territories in 
Croatia to Milosevic. This would signal an end to Croatia as a 
state, Ejup Ganic, member of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, 
said in his interview to VJESNIK and VECER. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

