<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatian, B-H Leaders Meet To Discuss Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Croatians Plan `Important' Announcement </H4>
<F P=102> AU0501111094 Paris AFP in English 1050 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, Jan 5 (AFP) -- The Croatian delegation at 
bilateral talks here with Bosnian leaders said an "important" 
announcement would be made at midday, as talks resumed after 
failing to reach a cease-fire agreement Tuesday [4 January]. 
The Croat delegation said the announcement would be made at 
noon (1100 GMT), on the second day of discussions in the old 
imperial palace at Hofburg. The talks were expected to focus on 
a ceasefire, internal borders and access to the sea for the 
Bosnian Moslems. 
  The Vienna-based U.S. ambassador to Bosnia-Hercegovina, 
Victor Jakovich, was at Wednesday's opening of the talks, but 
the international mediators Lord Owen for the European Community 
and Thorvald Stoltenberg for the UN, who attended on Tuesday, 
were not present. 
  The two delegation chiefs, Bosnian Prime Minister Haris 
Silajdzic and Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic, both 
described their discussions on Tuesday afternoon as 
"constructive." They said "real progress" had been made on the 
passage of humanitarian convoys and prisoner swaps. 
  Silajdzic also said he was "encouraged" by a Craotian pledge 
supported Bosnian proposals to allow residents of Mostar, a 
southern Bosnian city hit hard by the ethnic conflict, to return 
home. The talks here follow a recent escalation of fighting 
between mainly Moslem Bosnian and Bosnian Croat forces in 
central Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

