<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kucan Hails Proposal for UN Special Envoy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0401163294 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1430 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0401163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Regarding the letter of U.S. President Bill Clinton 
referring to the arrival of his special envoy Madeleine 
Albright, President Milan Kucan concluded that the initiative of 
President Clinton is highly important and welcome in Slovenia. 
Ambassador Albright will brief the Slovene leadership with the 
conclusions of the NATO summit that will take place on 10 and 11 
January. This will primarily involve NATO's security 
cooperation with Central and East European countries and the 
so-called partnership for peace. In Kucan's opinion this issue 
is very important for Slovenia, which is a small country with 
rather limited possibilities for investment into armament. 
However, other issues that will supposedly be discussed are 
also interesting for Slovenia, for example, the issues 
concerning the functioning of the United Nations, part of which 
are humanitarian aid, implementation of measures, work of the 
war crimes tribunal, and expansion of the UN Security Council. 
  Milan Kucan also believes that the talks with Madeleine 
Albright in Slovenia will also be an opportunity to discuss 
relations between the states, as Ms. Albright is a good 
connoisseur of the situation in Slovenia and in the region. 

</TEXT>

